	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">The Ultimate Kindness</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/pema-chodron">Pema Chödrön</a></li><li><a href="/issues/369">September 2006</a></li></ul>

			</div>

																			

				<figure class="block-content-photo block-content-photo-large photo photo-outset-center-small">
					
					<img src="data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,%3Csvg xmlns%3D'http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg' viewBox%3D'0 0 1589 1960'%2F%3E"
		data-src=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/795x980r/photos/369-20-carter.jpg data-src-retina=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/1589x1960r/photos/369-20-carter.jpg
	 alt="369 - Carter - Chodron"
	 class="lazy">

										<figcaption>

						
																				<div class="photo-credit">
								&copy;&nbsp;<a href="/contributors/william-carter">William Carter</a>
							</div>
																		</figcaption>
									</figure>

					</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<p class="dropcap">War and peace start in the hearts of individuals. Strangely enough, even though all beings would like to live in peace, our method for obtaining peace over the generations seems not to be very effective: we seek peace and happiness by going to war. This can occur at the level of our domestic situation, in our relationships with those close to us. Maybe we come home from work and we&rsquo;re tired and we just want some peace; but at home all hell is breaking loose for one reason or another, and so we start yelling at people. What is our motivation? We want some happiness and ease and peace, but what we do is get even more worked up, and we get everyone else worked up too. This is a familiar scenario in our homes, in our workplaces, in our communities, even when we&rsquo;re just driving our cars. We&rsquo;re just driving along, and someone cuts in front of us, and then what? Well, we don&rsquo;t like it, so we roll down the window and scream at them.</p>

<p>War begins when we harden our hearts, and we harden them easily &mdash; in minor ways and then in quite serious, major ways, such as hatred and prejudice &mdash; whenever we feel uncomfortable. It&rsquo;s so sad, really, because our motivation in hardening our hearts is to find some kind of ease, some kind of freedom from the distress that we&rsquo;re feeling.</p>

<p>Someone once gave me a poem with a line in it that offers a good definition of peace: &ldquo;Softening what is rigid in our hearts.&rdquo; We can talk about ending war and we can march for ending war, we can do everything in our power, but war is never going to end as long as our hearts are hardened against each other.</p>

<p>What happens is a chain reaction, and I&rsquo;d be surprised if you didn&rsquo;t know what I&rsquo;m talking about. Something occurs &mdash; it can be as small as a mosquito buzzing &mdash; and you tighten. If it&rsquo;s more than a mosquito (or maybe a mosquito is enough for you), something starts to shut down in you, and the next thing you know, imperceptibly, the chain reaction of misery begins: we begin to fan the grievance with our thoughts. These thoughts become the fuel that ignites war. War could be that you smash that little teensy-weensy mosquito. But I&rsquo;m also talking about war within the family, war at the office, war on the streets, and also war between nations, war in the world.</p>

<p>We often complain about other people&rsquo;s fundamentalism. But whenever we harden our hearts, what is going on with us? There&rsquo;s an uneasiness and then a tightening, a shutting down, and then the next thing we know, the chain reaction begins and we become very righteous about our right to kill the mosquito or yell at the person in the car or whatever it might be. We ourselves become fundamentalists, which is to say we become self-righteous about our personal point of view. Jarvis Masters, who is a prisoner on death row, has written one of my favorite spiritual books, called <em>Finding Freedom</em>. In a chapter called &ldquo;Angry Faces,&rdquo; Jarvis has his <span class="smallcaps">TV</span> on in his cell, but he doesn&rsquo;t have the sound on because he&rsquo;s using the light of the <span class="smallcaps">TV</span> to read by. And every once in a while, he looks up at the screen, then yells to people down the cellblock to ask what&rsquo;s happening.</p>

<p>The first time, someone yells back, &ldquo;It&rsquo;s the Ku Klux Klan, Jarvis, and they&rsquo;re all yelling and complaining about how it&rsquo;s the blacks and the Jews who are responsible for all these problems.&rdquo; About half an hour later, he yells again, &ldquo;Hey, what&rsquo;s happening now?&rdquo; And a voice calls back, &ldquo;That&rsquo;s the Greenpeace folks. They&rsquo;re demonstrating about the fact that the rivers are being polluted and the trees are being cut down and the animals are being hurt and our earth is being destroyed.&rdquo; Sometime later, he calls out again, &ldquo;Now what&rsquo;s going on?&rdquo; And someone says, &ldquo;Oh, Jarvis, that&rsquo;s the U.S. Senate, and that guy who&rsquo;s up there now talking, he&rsquo;s blaming the other guys, the other side, the other political party, for all the financial difficulty this country&rsquo;s in.&rdquo; Jarvis starts laughing, and he calls down, &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve learned something here tonight. Sometimes they&rsquo;re wearing Klan outfits, sometimes they&rsquo;re wearing Greenpeace outfits, sometimes they&rsquo;re wearing suits and ties, but they all have the same angry faces.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I remember reading once about a peace march. When one group was coming back from the march, some pro-war people started cutting them off and blocking them; everyone started screaming and hitting each other. I thought, <em>Wait a minute. Is there something wrong with this picture? Clobbering people with your peace sign?</em> The next time you get angry, check out your righteous indignation; check out your fundamentalism that supports your hatred of this person, because this one really <em>is</em> bad &mdash; this politician, that leader, those heads of big companies. Or maybe it&rsquo;s rage at an individual who has harmed you personally or harmed your loved ones. A fundamentalist mind is a mind that has become rigid. First the heart closes; then the mind becomes hardened into a view; then you can justify your hatred of another human being because of what they represent and what they say and do.</p>

<p>If you look back at history or you look at any place in the world where religious groups or ethnic groups or racial groups or political groups are killing each other, or families have been feuding for years and years, you can see &mdash; because you&rsquo;re not invested in that particular argument &mdash; that there will never be peace until somebody softens what is rigid in their heart. So it&rsquo;s necessary to take a big perspective on your own righteousness and your own fundamentalism when it begins to kick in and you think your own aggression and prejudice are reasonable.</p>

<p>I try to practice what I preach; I&rsquo;m not always that good at it, but I really do try. The other night, I was getting hardhearted, closed-minded, and fundamentalist about somebody else, and I remembered this expression that you can never hate somebody if you stand in that person&rsquo;s shoes. I was angry at him because he was holding such a rigid view. In that instant I was able to put myself in his shoes, and I realized, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m just as riled up and self-righteous and closed-minded about this as he is. We&rsquo;re in exactly the same place!&rdquo; And I saw that the more I held on to my view, the more polarized we would become, and the more we&rsquo;d be just mirror images of one another &mdash; two people with closed minds and hard hearts who both think they&rsquo;re right, screaming at each other. It changed for me when I saw it from his side, and I was able to see my own aggression and ridiculousness.</p>

<p>If you could have a bird&rsquo;s-eye perspective on the earth and could look down at all the conflicts that are happening, all you&rsquo;d see are two sides to a story where both sides think they&rsquo;re right. So the solutions have to come from a change of heart, from softening what is rigid in our hearts and minds.</p>

<p>One of the most inspiring modern examples we have of this is the civil-rights movement. I was recently rereading the writings of Martin Luther King Jr., and I understood once again that the whole movement was based on love &mdash; love that doesn&rsquo;t exclude anybody. This is also the Buddhist idea of love. In this view, you want everybody to be healed.</p>

<p>Now, some political activists might say, &ldquo;OK, but nothing will ever change just by holding that all-inclusive, loving view.&rdquo; But the truth is, when you take that view and you begin to live by it, at the level of your own heart in your own everyday life, something begins to shift dramatically, and you begin to see things in a different way. You begin to have the clarity to see injustice happening, but you can also see that injustice, by its very definition, is harming everybody involved. It&rsquo;s harming the people who are being oppressed or abused, and it&rsquo;s harming those who are oppressing and abusing.</p>

<p>And from a Buddhist point of view, those who are being oppressed have a chance &mdash; just as people did in the civil-rights movement &mdash; to be purified by what is happening to them. They have the opportunity to let hatred be replaced by love and compassion and to try to bring about change by nonviolence and nonaggression. Instead of sinking into self-absorption, they have a chance to let their suffering link them with the suffering of all beings &mdash; those harming, those helping, and those feeling neutral. In other words, they have a chance to soften what is rigid in their hearts and still hold the view that injustice is being done and work toward unwinding that injustice or that cruelty.</p>

<p>But those who are oppressing may be so prejudiced and rigid in their minds that there&rsquo;s very little opportunity for them to grow and learn. So they&rsquo;re the ones who ultimately suffer the most, because their own hatred and anger and prejudice continue to grow. There is nothing that causes more pain and suffering than to be consumed by bigotry, to be consumed by cruelty and anger.</p>

<p>So war and peace start in the human heart. Whether that heart is open or whether that heart closes has global implications.</p>

<p>Recently I was teaching from a Buddhist text called <em>The Way of the Bodhisattva</em>, which offers guidance to those who wish to dedicate their lives to alleviating suffering and to bringing benefit to all sentient beings. This was composed in the eighth century in India by a Buddhist master named Shantideva. In it he has an interesting point to make about peace. He says something along the lines of &ldquo;If these long-lived, ancient, aggressive patterns of mine that are the wellspring only of unceasing woe, that lead to my own suffering as well as the suffering of others &mdash; if these patterns still find their lodging safe within my heart, how can joy and peace in this world ever be found?&rdquo;</p>

<p>Shantideva is saying that as long as we justify our own hardheartedness and our own self-righteousness, joy and peace will always elude us. We point our fingers at the wrongdoers, but we ourselves are mirror images; everyone is outraged at everyone else&rsquo;s wrongness.</p>

<p>And then Shantideva makes another thought-provoking point. He says that the people whom we get so upset at, they eventually move away or they die. And likewise, with nations that fight each other, time passes, and either the nations no longer exist or they shift alliances, and enemies become allies. He reminds us how everything changes with time. But the negative seeds that are left in our mind-stream, the impact of our hatred and our prejudice, are very long-lived. Why so? Because as long as we keep strengthening our anger and self-righteousness with our thoughts and our words and our actions, they will never go away. Instead we become expert at perfecting our habits of hardheartedness, our own particular brand of rigid heart and closed mind.</p>

<p class="ckeditor-shortcode"><figure class="photo photo-outset-center-small">
	<div>
					<div>
				<img src="data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,%3Csvg xmlns%3D'http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg' viewBox%3D'0 0 1560 1629'%2F%3E"
		data-src=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/780x815r/photos/369-22-sugerman.jpg data-src-retina=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/1560x1629r/photos/369-22-sugerman.jpg
	 alt="369 - Sugarman - Chodron"
	 class="lazy">

									<figcaption>
																											<div class="photo-credit">
																			© <a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/contributors/debra-sugerman">
											Debra
																						Sugerman
										</a>
																	</div>
																								</figcaption>
							</div>
			</div>
</figure>
</p>

<p>So what I&rsquo;m advocating here is something that requires courage &mdash; the courage to have a change of heart. The reason this requires courage is because when we don&rsquo;t do the habitual thing, hardening our heart and holding tightly to certain views, then we&rsquo;re left with the underlying uneasiness that we were trying to get away from. Whenever there&rsquo;s a sense of threat, we harden. And so if we don&rsquo;t harden, what happens? We&rsquo;re left with that uneasiness, that feeling of threat. That&rsquo;s when the real journey of courage begins. This is the real work of the peacemaker, to find the soft spot and the tenderness in that uneasy place and stay with it. If we can stay with the soft spot and stay with the tender heart, then we are cultivating the seeds of peace.</p>

<p>I think to do this kind of work it&rsquo;s very helpful to take some sort of personal vow. You make it clear in your own mind what you wish for, and then you make a vow. For instance, let&rsquo;s say you hit your children and it&rsquo;s habitual, but then you make a vow to yourself: &ldquo;Whatever happens, I&rsquo;m not going to hit them.&rdquo; You seek help, and you look everywhere for ways to help you not hit them when that uneasiness arises and everything in you wants to close your heart and mind and go on automatic pilot and do the thing that you always hate yourself for doing. You vow that to the best of your ability &mdash; knowing that sometimes there&rsquo;s going to be backsliding, but nevertheless, to the best of your ability &mdash; you vow not to cause harm to yourself or to anybody else, and actually to help yourself and your children.</p>

<p>This kind of vow should be put in words that are meaningful and true to you so they aren&rsquo;t somebody else&rsquo;s good thoughts but actually your own highest, heartfelt wish for yourself. Your motivation behind the vow is that you equate it with the ultimate kindness for yourself, not the ultimate punishment or the ultimate shaping up, like &ldquo;I&rsquo;m bad; I need to shape up.&rdquo; No, the basic view is that there&rsquo;s nothing wrong with you or me or anybody else.</p>

<p>It&rsquo;s like what the Zen master Suzuki Roshi once said. He looked out at his students and said, &ldquo;All of you are perfect just as you are, and you could use a little improvement.&rdquo; That&rsquo;s how it is. You don&rsquo;t start from the view of &ldquo;I&rsquo;m fundamentally messed up, and I&rsquo;m bad, and therefore I have to get myself into shape.&rdquo; Rather the basic situation is good; it&rsquo;s sound and healthy and noble, <em>and</em> there&rsquo;s work that we need to do because we have ancient habits, which we&rsquo;ve been strengthening for a long time, and it&rsquo;s going to take a while to unwind them.</p>

<p>Living by a vow is very helpful, and actually it&rsquo;s Jarvis Masters who caused me to think about this. His Tibetan teacher, Chagdud Tulku Rinpoche, went to San Quentin Prison and, through the glass, talking over a telephone, did an empowerment ceremony in which Jarvis took the vow never to cause harm and, to the best of his ability, to try to help. He has lived by these vows earnestly, and when I read his book, sometimes I laugh out loud at the extremes to which he has to go not to cause harm in a place like San Quentin.</p>

<p>To prevent some hostile, disrespectful guards from being killed, for instance, he had to talk some angry inmates into flooding their cells, because they needed a way to express their rage. He knew that if he didn&rsquo;t come up with something, they were planning to retaliate by stabbing the guards. So instead he said, &ldquo;Listen, the whole thing is, you don&rsquo;t need to kill them. These guys are wanting to get out of here to go to a party, so you just need to ruin their day by making them work late cleaning up the mess we&rsquo;ll make.&rdquo; And everyone bought it; so they just flooded the tier.</p>

<p>One of my favorite stories about Jarvis was when he unintentionally helped some other inmates connect with the absolute, vast quality of their own minds. There is a teaching that says that behind all hardening and tightening and rigidity of the heart, there&rsquo;s always fear. But if you touch fear, behind fear there is a soft spot. And if you touch that soft spot, you find the vast blue sky. You find that which is ineffable, ungraspable, and unbiased, that which can support and awaken us at any time. And somehow Jarvis, in this story of trying to avert harm, conveyed this fundamental openness to the other inmates.</p>

<p>One day there was a sea gull out on the yard in San Quentin. It had been raining, and the sea gull was there paddling around in a puddle. One of the inmates picked up something in the yard and was about to throw it at the bird. Jarvis didn&rsquo;t even think about it &mdash; he automatically put out his hand to stop the man. Of course this escalated the man&rsquo;s aggression, and he started yelling: Who the hell did Jarvis think he was? And why did Jarvis care so much about some blankety-blank bird?</p>

<p>Everyone started circling around, just waiting for the fight. The other inmate was screaming at Jarvis, &ldquo;Why&rsquo;d you do that?&rdquo; And out of Jarvis&rsquo;s mouth came the words &ldquo;I did it because that bird&rsquo;s got my wings.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Everyone got it. It simply stopped their minds, softened their hearts, and then there was silence. Then they all started laughing and joking with him. Even years later, they still tease him, &ldquo;What did you mean, Jarvis, &lsquo;That bird&rsquo;s got my wings&rsquo;?&rdquo; But at that moment, everyone understood.</p>

<p>If we begin to take responsibility for our own self-righteousness, it leads to empathy. Here&rsquo;s one more Jarvis story to illustrate this: Many of the prison guards in San Quentin are kind and helpful, but some of them get mean and unreasonable and take their frustrations out on the prisoners. One day there had been plenty of that happening, and tempers were short. An inmate came up to Jarvis in the yard and asked, &ldquo;Is it your Buddhism that keeps you so calm, Jarvis? How can you stand it when these guards are giving you such shit?&rdquo;</p>

<p>And Jarvis said, &ldquo;Oh, it has nothing to do with Buddhism. I just think that if I retaliate, they&rsquo;ll go home and beat their kids. I don&rsquo;t want that to happen to any of those little kids.&rdquo; The other man got it completely. Our empathy and wisdom begin to come forward when we&rsquo;re not clouded by our rigid views or our closed heart. It&rsquo;s common sense. &ldquo;If I retaliate, then they&rsquo;ll go home and beat their kids, and I don&rsquo;t want that happening.&rdquo;</p>

<p>There are many stories, but the basic message I&rsquo;m trying to convey is that to the degree that each of us is dedicated to wanting there to be peace in the world, then we have to take responsibility when our own hearts and minds harden and close. We have to be brave enough to soften what is rigid, to find the soft spot and stay with it. We have to have that kind of courage and take that kind of responsibility. That&rsquo;s true spiritual warriorship. That&rsquo;s the true practice of peace.</p>

<hr />
<p><em>&ldquo;The Ultimate Kindness&rdquo; is excerpted from </em>Practicing Peace in Times of War<em>, by American Buddhist nun Pema Ch&ouml;dr&ouml;n. </em>&copy;<em> 2006 by Pema Ch&ouml;dr&ouml;n. The book has just been published, with text based on talks given by the author and edited by Sandy Boucher. It appears here by permission of Shambhala Publications, Inc. (<a href="http://www.shambhala.com">www.shambhala.com</a>).</em></p>

<p class="text-right"><em>&mdash; Ed.</em></p>
														</div>


				
